    <p>
        <term>Key Takeaway</term> 
    </p>

    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Two figures are considered similar when their corresponding sides have the same ratio.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    In the case of flat (plane) shapes, their matching interior angles must also be equal.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    When naming similar triangles, list the vertices in a way that shows which angles are equal.
                    For instance, if triangle <m>ABC</m> is similar to triangle <m>DEF</m>, it means angle  <m>A</m> matches angle <m>D</m>,
                    angle <m>B</m> matches angle <m>E</m>, and angle <m>C</m> matches angle <m>F</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine whether triangle <m>PQR</m> and triangle <m>XYZ</m> are similar.
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                            % Coordinates
                            \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                            \coordinate (Q) at (12,0);

                            % Coordinates of R using polar coordinates
                            \coordinate (R) at ({8*cos(26.4)}, {8*sin(26.4)});

                            % Fill the triangle with blue color
                            \fill[blue!30] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                            % Draw the triangle outline
                            \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                            % Label the points
                            \node[below left] at (P) {P};
                            \node[below right] at (Q) {Q};
                            \node[above] at (R) {R};

                            % Add side lengths
                            \node[below] at (6,0) {12 cm};
                            \path (P) -- (R) node[midway,left] {8 cm};
                            \path (Q) -- (R) node[midway,right] {6 cm};
                         \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>

                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                        % Coordinates
                        \coordinate (X) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Y) at (12,0);

                        % Coordinates of Z using polar coordinates
                        \coordinate (Z) at ({8*cos(26.4)}, {8*sin(26.4)});

                        % Fill the triangle with green color
                        \fill[green!30] (X) -- (Y) -- (Z) -- cycle;

                        % Draw the triangle outline
                        \draw[thick] (X) -- (Y) -- (Z) -- cycle;

                        % Label the points
                        \node[below left] at (X) {X};
                        \node[below right] at (Y) {Y};
                        \node[above] at (Z) {Z};

                        % Add side lengths
                        \node[below] at (6,0) {24 cm};
                        \path (X) -- (Z) node[midway,left] {16 cm};
                        \path (Y) -- (Z) node[midway,right] {12 cm};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>PR</m> corresponds to <m>XZ</m>, <m>PQ</m> corresponds to <m>XY</m>, and <m>QR</m> corresponds to <m>YZ</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{Therefore,} \amp \frac{PR}{XZ}= \frac{PQ}{XY}= \frac {QR}{YZ} </mrow>
                <mrow> =\amp \frac{8\, cm}{16\, cm}= \frac{12\, cm}{24\, cm}= \frac {6\, cm}{12\, cm} </mrow>
                <mrow> \frac{1}{2}= \frac{1}{2}=\amp \frac{1}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Since corresponding sides are proportional, we conclude that triangle <m>PQR</m> is similar to triangle <m>XYZ</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>



